sentences: Bob Parlocha was born in Solano, California, in 1938, to Maria Carter and Carlos Parlocha.
He graduated from Vallejo High School in 1956.
This resulted in Parlocha's appointment as host of the "Dinner Jazz Show," in 1978.
Parlocha engineered the late Martha Young's album Live at Bajone's on the Carnelian label, and Sufi Dancers for pianist Steve Cohn, both in 1982.
He also produced a number of albums; his first in 1985 was singer Laurie Antonioli's "Soul Eyes" on Catero Records.
A decline in jazz radio audiences led KJAZ owner Ron Cowan to sell the ailing station in 1994.
WGBH-FM, in Boston, Massachusetts, has carried the show for decades, albeit with some glitches in their transition to "mostly talk" radio in 2009.
The leading jazz station in the western United States, KKJZ (Long Beach), began airing his program in early 2007.
He also performed as a saxophonist, appearing regularly with the Bob Enos big band, Soundwave, at Rooster's Roadhouse in Alameda and in events such as at the 2008 San Jose Jazz Festival.

sentences: Robert "Bob" Parlocha (April 18, 1938 – March 15, 2015) was an American jazz expert who was best known as a radio host and programmer.
He was in wide syndication with his nighttime jazz show Jazz With Bob Parlocha.
Jazz remained a hobby for the next decade, while he worked as a psychiatric nurse at UCSF.
KJAZ owner Pat Henry's on-air invitation to prospective DJs led Parlocha to submit a tape, prompting Henry to hire him as a programmer for the station's Saturday evenings.
A thoughtful programmer, articulate spokesman for jazz, and analyst of the music scene, his "master of ceremonies" style enhanced many jazz concerts and fundraisers over the subsequent years.
The evening show was picked up by KUVO (Denver), WRCJ-FM (Detroit) and several other public radio stations, including Kansas and Alabama.
WGBH-FM, in Boston, Massachusetts, has carried the show for decades, albeit with some glitches in their transition to "mostly talk" radio in 2009.
Within 4 months following his death, KKJZ dropped Bob's recorded syndicated programming, with Bob's playlists on WFMT's website also disappearing in that time period.
WFMT continues to offer a Jazz overnight service with hosts Dee Alexander, John Hill, Dave Schwan, and Neil Tesser.
